From two os these later entrieS, articles 17 and 22, it will be seen that the MS. passed into the hands of some one connected with the family of Humphrey Bohun, earl of Hereford and Northampton. His death and that of his mother-in-law are recorded; and we have also the medical case os his widow‚ wh0, as mother of king Henry the fourth’s late wife, Mary Bohun, is attended by the royal physician in 1408. From the fact of this case being entered in the MS„ and from the character os the other additions, it seems not improbable that the volume became the property of the physician of the family. But there is also evidence os a still earlier link between the MS. and the BohunS, dating back to the time of its compilation. For Thomas de Walmes- ford, in whose favour the award was made, as recorded in article 9 which forms a part os the original contents, was in 1328 presented to the rectory of Shenfield in Essex, and again in 1334 to the rectory of Lees Magna or Much Lees in the same county, by John de Bohun, earl of Hereford, who died in 1335.
